5|$|In {{the spring}} of 1916 he was {{transferred}} as first lieutenant to a <b>Q-ship</b> under Gordon Campbell. A <b>Q-ship</b> was a merchant ship with hidden weaponry, commanded secretly by the navy and manned by a Royal Navy crew. When attacked by a submarine, the <b>Q-ship</b> would feign damage until the enemy {{was close enough to}} engage and then reveal its weapons to counter-attack. Campbell, a major proponent of <b>Q-ship</b> strategy, was impressed with Stuart's stubborn refusal to accept the two years of rejection and brought him in to replace an officer whose nerves had cracked under the strain of <b>Q-ship</b> operations.|$|E
5|$|In {{addition}} to receiving the Victoria Cross, Stuart {{was promoted to}} lieutenant commander and given his own command, HMS Tamarisk. Tamarisk was a small sloop built in 1916 that was capable of being disguised as a merchant vessel and used as a <b>Q-ship,</b> designated Q11.|$|E
5|$|Six {{days into}} her first war patrol, on 22 March 1916, U-68 was sunk by , a British <b>Q-ship,</b> with all hands. U-68 sank no ships in her brief career. A post-war German study found fault with U-68s captain for not {{following}} established procedures for avoiding decoy ships.|$|E
