500|$|U-68 {{was laid}} down on 31 December 1913 (yard number 205) by Germaniawerft at Kiel and {{launched}} on 1 June 1915. She was commissioned on 17 August 1915 {{under the command}} of Kapitänleutnant Ludwig Güntzel. Six days into her first war patrol, U-68 encountered the British <b>Q-ship</b> [...] (<b>Q-ship</b> number five) off Dingle and was sunk with all hands. U-68 sank no ships during her brief service career.|$|E
500|$|Seiner Majestät UB-4 was a German Type UB I {{submarine}} (U-boat) in the German Imperial Navy (...) during World War I. She was sunk by a British <b>Q-ship</b> {{disguised as}} a fishing smack in August 1915.|$|E
500|$|His Majesty's or HM Armed Smack Inverlyon was {{a fishing}} smack that was {{converted}} to a <b>Q-ship</b> during the First World War. Q-ships served as decoys to lure German submarines near enough so that concealed weapons could {{be brought to bear}} and sink the submarines. On 15 August 1915, Inverlyon succeeded in luring German submarine [...] within range and sinking her with nine shots from her gun. The Royal Navy [...] in command of the vessel, Ernest Martin Jehan, received the Distinguished Service Cross and members of Inverlyons crew shared the bounty offered for German submarines. After Inverlyons <b>Q-ship</b> career ended, she returned to fishing, but was sunk by [...] on 1 February 1917.|$|E
500|$|His conduct on Helgoland {{resulted}} in a promotion to lieutenant for Sanders, {{and he was also}} recommended for command of his own ship. [...] In February 1917, he was appointed captain of HMS Prize, a three-masted topsail schooner that was sailing under the German flag when it was seized in 1914 and converted to a <b>Q-ship</b> in early 1917. [...] At midnight on 30 April 1917 about 180 miles south of Ireland, in the Atlantic, Prize was attacked by a U-boat, [...] commanded by Edgar von Spiegel von und zu Peckelsheim. The <b>Q-ship</b> was genuinely badly damaged by shellfire from the U-boat's deck guns. [...] Sanders, remaining under cover, moved about the vessel reassuring his men.|$|E
500|$|One method {{devised to}} deal with U-boat attacks was the decoy or <b>Q-ship,</b> {{designed}} to lure submarines that were targeting merchant shipping close enough so that concealed guns or other weapons could sink them. Inverlyon was selected to become a <b>Q-ship,</b> was outfitted with either a 3-pounder (47mm) or a 6-pounder (57mm) gun, and entered {{the service of the}} Royal Navy on 2 August 1915. Inverlyons fishing crew and skipper were all temporarily inducted into the Trawler section of the Royal Naval Reserve. Regular Royal Navy [...] Ernest Martin Jehan and three other gunners from —a former torpedo boat operating as a minesweeper out of Lowestoft—were assigned to Inverlyon, with Jehan in command.|$|E
500|$|Not {{until after}} the war was it learned [...] had sunk Irish Oak. This action, and U-607s report, were not well received. Her Captain, Oberleutnant zur See Wolf Jeschonnek, claimed Irish Oak was a <b>Q-ship</b> with false Irish markings, sailing without lights.|$|E
500|$|UB-4 {{conducted}} the first sortie of the Flanders Flotilla in April, {{during which she}} sank the Belgian Relief ship , the first ship credited to the flotilla. She sank three more ships from mid-April to mid-August. On 15 August, UB-4 surfaced near the British <b>Q-ship</b> [...] and was sunk by gunfire from the sailing vessel. None of UB-4s 14 crewmen survived the attack.|$|E
500|$|For {{his role}} in the sinking of the UC-33, Worsley was awarded the Distinguished Service Order (DSO) and Shackleton sent him a {{telegraph}} congratulating him on his success. [...] Worsley conducted patrols with the PC.61 for several more months. In September 1918, he was given command of HMS Pangloss, a <b>Q-ship</b> operating in the Mediterranean and which was formerly commanded by Commander Gordon Campbell. With the war nearly over, Worsley did not anticipate much excitement in his new posting.|$|E
